{"title_page": "Abbas I of Egypt", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{Infobox monarch\n|name            =Abbas Helmy I<br/>\u0639\u0628\u0627\u0633 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0648\u0644\n|succession      =[[W\u0101li]] of [[Egypt under Muhammad Ali and his successors|Egypt]] and [[History of Sudan under Muhammad Ali and his successors|Sudan]]<br>\n[[File:Coat of arms of the Egyptian Kingdom 2.png|50px]]\n|image=Abbas_I1.png\n|caption         =\n|reign           =10 November 1848 \u2013 13 July 1854<ref>{{harvnb|Williams|1999|p=248}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Williams|1999|p=253}}</ref>\n|native_lang1     =[[Arabic language|Arabic]]\n|native_lang1_name1=\u0639\u0628\u0627\u0633 \u062d\u0644\u0645\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0648\u0644 \n|predecessor     =[[Ibrahim Pasha of Egypt|Ibrahim Pasha]]\n|successor       =[[Sa'id of Egypt|Sa'id Pasha]]\n|spouse 1        =[[Mahivech Hanim]]\n|spouse 2        =Shazdil Qadin\n|spouse 3        =Hawaya Qadin\n|spouse 4        =Hamdam Qadin\n|spouse 5        =Barlanta Qadin\n|issue           =[[Damad Prince Ibrahim Ilhamy Pasha]]<br>Mustafa<br>Havva<br>Mehmed Sad\u0131k<br>Ay\u015fe S\u0131d\u0131ka\n|dynasty         =[[Muhammad Ali Dynasty]]\n|father          =[[Tusun Pasha]]\n|mother          =[[Bamba Qadin]]\n|birth_date   =1 July 1812\n|birth_place  =[[Jeddah]], [[Hejaz]]\n|death_date   ={{death date and age|1854|7|13|1812|7|1|df=yes}}\n|death_place  =[[Banha]], Egypt\n|date of burial  =\n|place of burial = [[Hosh al-Basha]] Mausoleum of Imam al-Shafi'i, [[Cairo]], [[Egypt]]\n|religion =[[Islam]]\n|spouse 6=Piralanat Hanim|spouse 7=Gul Hanim}}\n'''Abbas Helmy I of Egypt''' (also known as ''Abbas Pasha'', {{lang-ar|\u0639\u0628\u0627\u0633 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0648\u0644}}, {{lang-tr|I. Abbas Hilmi Pa\u015fa}} 1 July 1812{{snd}}13 July 1854)<ref name=EB>{{harvnb|Hoiberg|2010|p=8}}</ref> was the [[W\u0101li]] of [[Egypt]] and [[Sudan]]. He was a son of the Albanian [[Tusun Pasha]], and a grandson of the Albanian [[Muhammad Ali of Egypt|Muhammad Ali]], founder of the reigning [[Muhammad Ali Dynasty]] of [[Egypt]] and [[Sudan]].  The [[Chambers Biographical Dictionary]] says of him: \"[b]igoted and sensual, he did much to undo the progress made under [[Muhammad Ali of Egypt|Muhammad Ali]].\"<ref>{{harvnb|Thorne|1984|p=1}}</ref>\n\n==Early years==\nAbbas was born on 1 July 1812 in [[Jeddah]] and was brought up in Cairo.<ref name=boul99>{{harvnb|Goldschmidt, Jr.|2000|p=2}}</ref> Being the grandson of [[Muhammad Ali of Egypt|Muhammad Ali]], he succeeded his uncle [[Ibrahim Pasha of Egypt|Ibrahim Pasha]] in ruling Egypt and Sudan in 1848.<ref name=eb1911>{{harvnb|Chisholm|1911|p=9}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Anon|2009}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[al-Jabarti]], the leading historian of this time period, Abbas I was born in Cairo while his father, Tosun Pasha, was in the [[Hejaz]] fighting against the [[Wahabi]]st movement.{{citation needed|date=November 2013}} As a young man, he fought in the [[Levant]] under his uncle [[Ibrahim Pasha of Egypt|Ibrahim Pasha]] in the [[Egyptian\u2013Ottoman War (1839\u201341)|Syrian War]].<ref name=CD/> Muhammad Ali Pasha was removed from office on 1 September 1848, on account of mental weakness. He was replaced by his son Ibrahim Pasha, who reigned briefly as [[Regent]] of Egypt and Sudan from 1 September 1848 until his death on 10 November 1848. The death of Ibrahim made Abbas I, in turn, Regent of Egypt and Sudan from 10 November 1848 until 2 August 1849 (the date of Muhammad Ali Pasha's death), at which time Abbas became the reigning Wali of Egypt and Sudan until 13 July 1854.<ref name=eb1911/>\n\n==Ruler of Egypt==\nAbbas has been often described as a mere voluptuary, but [[Nubar Pasha]] spoke of him as a true gentleman of the \"old school\".<ref name=eb1911/> He was seen as reactionary, morose, and taciturn, and spent nearly all his time in his palace.<ref name =EB/> He undid, as far as lay in his power, the works of his grandfather, both good and bad. Among other things he abolished trade [[monopolies]], closed factories and schools, and reduced the strength of the region's army to 9,000 men.<ref name=eb1911/> He also shut down construction of the [[Delta Barrage|Delta Dam]] and opposed the construction of the [[Suez Canal]].<ref name=EB/><ref name=CD>{{harvnb|Magnusson|Goring|1990|p=2}}</ref>\n\n==Alexandria Rebellion==\nIn 1851 and after three years of Abbas' tyrannical rule, Egyptians were at the top of their madness. the governor of Alexandria 'Shereko' led large numbers of Alexandrian locals towards the army's guns and ammunitions factory in Alexandria and robbed all the guns and equipment there, a day later Shereko declared rebellion against the ruler (Abbas I) and the locals took their positions all over the city to defend it. When Abbas I heard about the rebellion, he sent 30,000 troops and tens of field guns and sieged the city bombing it with artillery for a full month, leading to the death of 300 Alexandrians. When Shereko the governor of Alexandria, knew that things aren't getting any better with Alexandria's infrastructure annihilated due to artillery bombardment, he decided to surrender. Abbas I then ordered to behead Shereko and drag his head all over the destroyed streets of Alexandria. After the rebellion, Abbas' anxiety increased even more that he exiled his uncle Sa'id (later [[Sa'id of Egypt]]) to Alexandria and all his family escaped to Europe after that.\n\n==Foreign Relations==\nHe was inaccessible to adventurers bent on plundering Egypt and Sudan of riches, and kicked out all foreign business; however at the insistence of the British government, [[Egyptian National Railways|he allowed the construction of a railway]] from [[Alexandria]] to [[Cairo]], in return the British assisted him in a dispute with the Ottoman Empire.<ref name=EB/><ref name=Colliers>{{harvnb|Vucinich|1997|p=7}}</ref> due to his policies to Europeans and their influence, he was not liked by them and in time his reputation was exaggerated and demonized to portray him as worse than he actually was.<ref name = Stearns>{{harvnb|Stearns|2001|p=543}}</ref> After he died the number of Europeans in Egypt rose drastically from 3,000, in 1850, to 90,000, in 1882, and 200,000 by 1900.<ref name=Stearns/>\n==Crimean War==\nDuring the [[Crimean War]] he gave the [[Sultan of Turkey]] use of his naval fleet and 19,000 soldiers and 12 warships. which was later increased to 40,000 soldiers.<ref name=Colliers/>\n\n==Horse breeding==\nAmong his personal interests was the breeding of [[Arabian horse]]s,  said to be the overriding passion of Abbas' life, and his development and acquisition of quality bloodlines was of immense influence upon the modern horse breed.<ref name=\"White\"/>  He continued a breeding program begun by Muhammad Ali.<ref name=\"Culbertson\"/>  Muhammad Ali and Abbas I both recognized the unique characteristics and paid careful attention to bloodlines of the horses bred by the [[Bedouin]].  At age 23, Abbas had been put in charge of the horse breeding program of his grandfather.<ref name=\"White\">{{cite web|last1=White|first1=Linda|title=Horse In History - Abbas Pasha Revisited|url=https://issuu.com/arabian-horse-times/docs/ed-history-abbapasha907a|website=Arabian Horse Times|accessdate=25 May 2017|language=en|date=September 2007}}</ref>   Upon becoming Wali, Abbas I accumulated additional horses and carefully documented the histories of the animals and their bloodlines in writing, records which have been preserved into the present day.<ref name=\"Culbertson\"/>   Through a connection with [[Faisal bin Turki bin Abdullah Al Saud|Faisal Ibn Saud]], for whom Abbas was said to have engineered an escape from a prison where he had been held, Abbas obtained a number of horses from the [[Nejd]]. He also paid very high prices for [[mare]]s of the best bloodlines from the [[Anazeh]] people. He built extensive stables for these horses in three different locations, including a [[stud farm]] said to have cost \u00a31,000,000 to build, and hired native Bedouin caretakers to oversee the care of the horses and to maintain information on their bloodlines.  He also spared no expense in the care of horses, at one farm keeping 300 camels available to provide extra milk for the young [[foal]]s.<ref name=\"White\"/>\n\n==Death==\nOn 13 July 1854,<ref name=Colliers/>  Abbas was murdered in [[Benha Palace]] by two of his slaves.<ref name=EB/> It was said that his cruelty to his servants was a motive.  As an example, a story conveyed to Arabian breeder [[Lady Anne Blunt]], told that Abbas I had once ordered a hot [[horseshoe]] to be nailed to the foot of a [[horse groom]] who had neglected the [[farrier]] care of a horse.<ref name=\"White\"/>  He was later succeeded by his uncle (who was actually younger than him), [[Sa'id of Egypt|Said Pasha]].<ref name=eb1911/><ref>{{harvnb|Stearns|2001|p=542}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his assassination, his Arabian horses were inherited by his eighteen-year-old son  [[Damad Prince Ibrahim Ilhamy Pasha]] (aka [[El Hami Pasha]]), who had little interest in them, giving away several and putting the rest up for auction. In 1861, a distant relative, [[Ali Pasha Sherif]] purchased approximately 40 horses of the original Abbas Pasha stock and rebuilt the horse breeding program.<ref name=\"Culbertson\">{{cite web|last1=Culbertson|first1=Cynthia|title=A Guide To Historical Names and Terms Associated with Egyptian Arabian Horse Breeding|url=http://desertheritagemagazine.com/NEW/articles/heritage/12_historicalnames.pdf|website=Desert Heritage Magazine|accessdate=24 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n{{refimprove section|date=September 2014}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Honours<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.royalark.net/Egypt/egypt7.htm|title=Egypt7|website=www.royalark.net|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n! year !! name !! Nation !! Ribbon\n|-\n|1849\n| Order of the August Portrait || [[Ottoman Empire]] ||\n|-\n| 1849 || [[Order of Glory (Ottoman Empire)|Order of Glory]] || Ottoman Empire || [[File:Order of Glory (Ottoman Empire) - ribbon bar.png|100px]]\n|-\n| 1853 || Order of Nobility, 1st Class || Ottoman Empire ||\n|-\n| || [[Order of Saints Maurice and Lazarus]], Grand Cross || [[Kingdom of Sardinia]] || [[File:Cavaliere di gran Croce Regno SSML BAR.svg|100px]]\n\n|}\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite web|author=Anon |date=20 July 2009 |title=14-Mohamed Ali's Dynasty |url=http://www.sis.gov.eg/En/Templates/Articles/tmpArticles.aspx?ArtID=1668#.VA_r4vldXF8 |accessdate=10 September 2014 |archivedate=10 September 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6STe6Ut7l?url=http://www.sis.gov.eg/En/Templates/Articles/tmpArticles.aspx?ArtID=1668 |url-status=live |website=Egypt: State Information Service |ref=harv |df=dmy }}\n* {{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Abbas I|volume=1|page=9 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book | last = Goldschmidt, Jr. | first = Arthur | title = Biographical Dictionary of Modern Egypt | year = 2000 | publisher = Lynne Rienner Pub. | location = Boulder, CO | url = https://archive.org/details/00jrgo | isbn = 1-5558-7229-8 | ref = harv | url-access = registration }} {{Subscription required|via=Questia}}\n* {{cite encyclopedia | editor-last = Hoiberg | editor-first = Dale H. | encyclopedia = Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica | title = Abbas I (Egypt) | edition = 15th | year = 2010 | publisher = Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, Inc. | volume = I: A\u2013Ak - Bayes | location = Chicago, IL | isbn = 978-1-59339-837-8 | ref = harv | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/newencyclopaedia2009ency }}\n* {{cite encyclopedia | editor1-last = Magnusson | editor1-first = Magnus | editor2-last = Goring | editor2-first = Rosemary | encyclopedia = Cambridge Biographical Dictionary | title = Abbas Pasha | isbn = 0-521-39518-6 | year = 1990 | publisher = Cambridge University Press | location = Cambridge, UK | ref = harv }}\n* {{cite encyclopedia | editor-last = Stearns | editor-first = Peter N. | encyclopedia = The Encyclopedia of World History: Ancient, Medieval, and Modern Chronologically Arranged | year = 2001 | publisher = Houghton Mifflin Company | location = Boston, MA | isbn = 0-395-65237-5 | edition = 6th | lccn = 2001024479 | title = The Middle East and Egypty, 1796-1914: e. Egypt | ref = harv }}\n* {{cite encyclopedia | editor-last = Thorne | editor-first = John | encyclopedia = [[Chambers Biographical Dictionary]] | isbn = 0-550-18022-2 | year = 1984 | publisher = Chambers Ltd. | location = Edinburgh, UK | ref = harv }}\n* {{cite encyclopedia | last = Vucinich | first = Wayne S. | editor-last = Johnston | editor-first = Bernard | encyclopedia = Collier's Encyclopedia | title = Abbas I | edition = 1st | year = 1997 | publisher = P. F. Collier | volume = I: A to Ameland | location = New York, NY | lccn = 96084127 | ref = harv }}\n* {{cite book | editor-last = Williams | editor-first = Neville | title = The Hutchison Chronology of World History | volume = III: The Changing World: 1776\u20131900 | publisher = Helicom Publishing Limited | location = Oxford, UK | year = 1999 | isbn = 1-85986-283-7 | ref = harv }}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Abbas I of Egypt}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hou|[[Muhammad Ali Dynasty]]|1 July|1812|13 July|1854}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ibrahim Pasha of Egypt|Ibrahim Pasha]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[W\u0101li]] of [[Egypt]] and [[Sudan]]\n|years=1849\u20131854}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Sa'id of Egypt|Sa'id Pasha]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Muhammad Ali Dynasty}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Abbas I of Egypt}}\n[[Category:1812 births]]\n[[Category:1854 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century Egyptian monarchs]]\n[[Category:Muhammad Ali dynasty]]\n[[Category:Ottoman governors of Egypt]]\n[[Category:Field marshals of the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:Field marshals of Egypt]]\n[[Category:Knights Grand Cross of the Order of Saints Maurice and Lazarus]]\n[[Category:People murdered in Egypt]]\n[[Category:Arabian breeders and trainers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{Infobox monarch\n|name            =Abbas Helmy I<br/>\u0639\u0628\u0627\u0633 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0648\u0644\n|succession      =[[W\u0101li]] of [[Egypt under Muhammad Ali and his successors|Egypt]] and [[History of Sudan under Muhammad Ali and his successors|Sudan]]<br>\n[[File:Coat of arms of the Egyptian Kingdom 2.png|50px]]\n|image=Abbas_I1.png\n|caption         =\n|reign           =10 November 1848 \u2013 13 July 1854<ref>{{harvnb|Williams|1999|p=248}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Williams|1999|p=253}}</ref>\n|native_lang1     =[[Arabic language|Arabic]]\n|native_lang1_name1=\u0639\u0628\u0627\u0633 \u062d\u0644\u0645\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0648\u0644 \n|predecessor     =[[Ibrahim Pasha of Egypt|Ibrahim Pasha]]\n|successor       =[[Sa'id of Egypt|Sa'id Pasha]]\n|spouse 1        =[[Mahivech Hanim]]\n|spouse 2        =Shazdil Qadin\n|spouse 3        =Hawaya Qadin\n|spouse 4        =Hamdam Qadin\n|spouse 5        =Barlanta Qadin\n|issue           =[[Damad Prince Ibrahim Ilhamy Pasha]]<br>Mustafa<br>Havva<br>Mehmed Sad\u0131k<br>Ay\u015fe S\u0131d\u0131ka\n|dynasty         =[[Muhammad Ali Dynasty]]\n|father          =[[Tusun Pasha]]\n|mother          =[[Bamba Qadin]]\n|birth_date   =1 July 1812\n|birth_place  =[[Jeddah]], [[Hejaz]]\n|death_date   ={{death date and age|1854|7|13|1812|7|1|df=yes}}\n|death_place  =[[Banha]], Egypt\n|date of burial  =\n|place of burial = [[Hosh al-Basha]] Mausoleum of Imam al-Shafi'i, [[Cairo]], [[Egypt]]\n|religion =[[Islam]]\n|spouse 6=Piralanat Hanim|spouse 7=Gul Hanim}}\n'''Abbas Helmy I of Egypt''' (also known as ''Abbas Pasha'', {{lang-ar|\u0639\u0628\u0627\u0633 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0648\u0644}}, {{lang-tr|I. Abbas Hilmi Pa\u015fa}} 1 July 1812{{snd}}13 July 1854)<ref name=EB>{{harvnb|Hoiberg|2010|p=8}}</ref> was the [[W\u0101li]] of [[Egypt]] and [[Sudan]]. He was a son of the Albanian [[Tusun Pasha]], and a grandson of the Albanian [[Muhammad Ali of Egypt|Muhammad Ali]], founder of the reigning [[Muhammad Ali Dynasty]] of [[Egypt]] and [[Sudan]].  The [[Chambers Biographical Dictionary]] says of him: \"[b]igoted and sensual, he did much to undo the progress made under [[Muhammad Ali of Egypt|Muhammad Ali]].\"<ref>{{harvnb|Thorne|1984|p=1}}</ref>\n\n==Early years==\nAbbas was born on 1 July 1812 in [[Jeddah]] and was brought up in Cairo.<ref name=boul99>{{harvnb|Goldschmidt, Jr.|2000|p=2}}</ref> Being the grandson of [[Muhammad Ali of Egypt|Muhammad Ali]], he succeeded his uncle [[Ibrahim Pasha of Egypt|Ibrahim Pasha]] in ruling Egypt and Sudan in 1848.<ref name=eb1911>{{harvnb|Chisholm|1911|p=9}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Anon|2009}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[al-Jabarti]], the leading historian of this time period, Abbas I was born in Cairo while his father, Tosun Pasha, was in the [[Hejaz]] fighting against the [[Wahabi]]st movement.{{citation needed|date=November 2013}} As a young man, he fought in the [[Levant]] under his uncle [[Ibrahim Pasha of Egypt|Ibrahim Pasha]] in the [[Egyptian\u2013Ottoman War (1839\u201341)|Syrian War]].<ref name=CD/> Muhammad Ali Pasha was removed from office on 1 September 1848, on account of mental weakness. He was replaced by his son Ibrahim Pasha, who reigned briefly as [[Regent]] of Egypt and Sudan from 1 September 1848 until his death on 10 November 1848. The death of Ibrahim made Abbas I, in turn, Regent of Egypt and Sudan from 10 November 1848 until 2 August 1849 (the date of Muhammad Ali Pasha's death), at which time Abbas became the reigning Wali of Egypt and Sudan until 13 July 1854.<ref name=eb1911/>\n\n==Ruler of Egypt==\nAbbas has been often described as a mere voluptuary, but [[Nubar Pasha]] spoke of him as a true gentleman of the \"old school\".<ref name=eb1911/> He was seen as reactionary, morose, and taciturn, and spent nearly all his time in his palace.<ref name =EB/> He undid, as far as lay in his power, the works of his grandfather, both good and bad. Among other things he abolished trade [[monopolies]], closed factories and schools, and reduced the strength of the region's army to 9,000 men.<ref name=eb1911/> He also shut down construction of the [[Delta Barrage|Delta Dam]] and opposed the construction of the [[Suez Canal]].<ref name=EB/><ref name=CD>{{harvnb|Magnusson|Goring|1990|p=2}}</ref>\n\n==Alexandria Rebellion==\nIn 1851 and after three years of Abbas' tyrannical rule, Egyptians were at the top of their madness. the governor of Alexandria 'Shereko' led large numbers of Alexandrian locals towards the army's guns and ammunitions factory in Alexandria and robbed all the guns and equipment there, a day later Shereko declared rebellion against the ruler ([[Abbas I]]) and the locals took their positions all over the city to defend it. When Abbas I heard about the rebellion, he sent 30,000 troops and tens of field guns and sieged the city bombing it with artillery for a full month, leading to the death of 300 Alexandrians. When Shereko the governor of Alexandria, knew that things aren't getting any better with Alexandria's infrastructure annihilated due to artillery bombardment, he decided to surrender. [[Abbas I]] then ordered to behead Shereko and drag his head all over the destroyed streets of Alexandria. After the rebellion, Abbas' anxiety increased even more that he exiled his uncle Sa'id (later [[Sa'id of Egypt]]) to Alexandria and all his family escaped to Europe after that.\n\n==Foreign Relations==\nHe was inaccessible to adventurers bent on plundering Egypt and Sudan of riches, and kicked out all foreign business; however at the insistence of the British government, [[Egyptian National Railways|he allowed the construction of a railway]] from [[Alexandria]] to [[Cairo]], in return the British assisted him in a dispute with the Ottoman Empire.<ref name=EB/><ref name=Colliers>{{harvnb|Vucinich|1997|p=7}}</ref> due to his policies to Europeans and their influence, he was not liked by them and in time his reputation was exaggerated and demonized to portray him as worse than he actually was.<ref name = Stearns>{{harvnb|Stearns|2001|p=543}}</ref> After he died the number of Europeans in Egypt rose drastically from 3,000, in 1850, to 90,000, in 1882, and 200,000 by 1900.<ref name=Stearns/>\n==Crimean War==\nDuring the [[Crimean War]] he gave the [[Sultan of Turkey]] use of his naval fleet and 19,000 soldiers and 12 warships. which was later increased to 40,000 soldiers.<ref name=Colliers/>\n\n==Horse breeding==\nAmong his personal interests was the breeding of [[Arabian horse]]s,  said to be the overriding passion of Abbas' life, and his development and acquisition of quality bloodlines was of immense influence upon the modern horse breed.<ref name=\"White\"/>  He continued a breeding program begun by Muhammad Ali.<ref name=\"Culbertson\"/>  Muhammad Ali and Abbas I both recognized the unique characteristics and paid careful attention to bloodlines of the horses bred by the [[Bedouin]].  At age 23, Abbas had been put in charge of the horse breeding program of his grandfather.<ref name=\"White\">{{cite web|last1=White|first1=Linda|title=Horse In History - Abbas Pasha Revisited|url=https://issuu.com/arabian-horse-times/docs/ed-history-abbapasha907a|website=Arabian Horse Times|accessdate=25 May 2017|language=en|date=September 2007}}</ref>   Upon becoming Wali, Abbas I accumulated additional horses and carefully documented the histories of the animals and their bloodlines in writing, records which have been preserved into the present day.<ref name=\"Culbertson\"/>   Through a connection with [[Faisal bin Turki bin Abdullah Al Saud|Faisal Ibn Saud]], for whom Abbas was said to have engineered an escape from a prison where he had been held, Abbas obtained a number of horses from the [[Nejd]]. He also paid very high prices for [[mare]]s of the best bloodlines from the [[Anazeh]] people. He built extensive stables for these horses in three different locations, including a [[stud farm]] said to have cost \u00a31,000,000 to build, and hired native Bedouin caretakers to oversee the care of the horses and to maintain information on their bloodlines.  He also spared no expense in the care of horses, at one farm keeping 300 camels available to provide extra milk for the young [[foal]]s.<ref name=\"White\"/>\n\n==Death==\nOn 13 July 1854,<ref name=Colliers/>  Abbas was murdered in [[Benha Palace]] by two of his slaves.<ref name=EB/> It was said that his cruelty to his servants was a motive.  As an example, a story conveyed to Arabian breeder [[Lady Anne Blunt]], told that Abbas I had once ordered a hot [[horseshoe]] to be nailed to the foot of a [[horse groom]] who had neglected the [[farrier]] care of a horse.<ref name=\"White\"/>  He was later succeeded by his uncle (who was actually younger than him), [[Sa'id of Egypt|Said Pasha]].<ref name=eb1911/><ref>{{harvnb|Stearns|2001|p=542}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his assassination, his Arabian horses were inherited by his eighteen-year-old son  [[Damad Prince Ibrahim Ilhamy Pasha]] (aka [[El Hami Pasha]]), who had little interest in them, giving away several and putting the rest up for auction. In 1861, a distant relative, [[Ali Pasha Sherif]] purchased approximately 40 horses of the original Abbas Pasha stock and rebuilt the horse breeding program.<ref name=\"Culbertson\">{{cite web|last1=Culbertson|first1=Cynthia|title=A Guide To Historical Names and Terms Associated with Egyptian Arabian Horse Breeding|url=http://desertheritagemagazine.com/NEW/articles/heritage/12_historicalnames.pdf|website=Desert Heritage Magazine|accessdate=24 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n{{refimprove section|date=September 2014}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Honours<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.royalark.net/Egypt/egypt7.htm|title=Egypt7|website=www.royalark.net|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n! year !! name !! Nation !! Ribbon\n|-\n|1849\n| Order of the August Portrait || [[Ottoman Empire]] ||\n|-\n| 1849 || [[Order of Glory (Ottoman Empire)|Order of Glory]] || Ottoman Empire || [[File:Orde